    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-05-06T09:40:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-05-06T09:40:00-05:00" n="96"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d96">
                <head>96. Notes of Telephone Conversation Between the President’s Assistant for
                    National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="from"
                        >Kissinger</persName>) and the Deputy Secretary of Defense (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PDM1" type="to">Packard</persName>)<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d96fn1">Source: Library of Congress, Manuscript Division, <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> Papers, Box 359, Telephone
                        Conversations, Chronological File, 1–14 May 1969. No classification
                        marking.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d96fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> told Packard the President
                        would probably go ahead with the treaty if Smith put into the draft the
                        changes that <gloss target="#t_DOD1">DOD</gloss> wanted.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1969-05-06T10:40:00-04:00">May 6, 1969, 10:40 a.m.</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> said he was calling Mel but could not reach him
                    and asked if <gloss target="#t_P1">P</gloss> was familiar with Seabed problem.
                        <gloss target="#t_P1">P</gloss> said just vaguely.<gloss target="#t_K1"
                        >K</gloss> said Mel opposed it at <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> but
                    called <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> after and said if we had to proceed he
                    would like to make sure it contained some amendments. <gloss target="#t_K1"
                        >K</gloss> said he wondered if he could get these changes. <gloss
                        target="#t_P1">P</gloss> said the main thing is that there is nothing in the
                    draft that would jeopardize their underwater capability. <gloss target="#t_K1"
                        >K</gloss> said President will probably go ahead with treaty but on the
                    condition that Gerry Smith puts into the draft the changes Defense wants. <gloss
                        target="#t_P1">P</gloss> asked when <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> wanted
                    it and <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> said by tomorrow morning. <gloss
                        target="#t_K1">K</gloss> said he is seeing Gerry Smith at 6:00p tomorrow
                    night at his office. President wants <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> to
                    negotiate this. <gloss target="#t_P1">P</gloss> said <gloss target="#t_K1"
                        >K</gloss> would have them by morning.</p>
            </div>
